{{Rewrite|date=08/05/2026|Alright, this is something. I'd say this barely skirts the standards, thus why this is a rewrite template instead of a deletion template.

The page overall suffers from writing issues, sentences like: "I've always wanted to work at NASA, but not like this mess.. the darkness is the only thing that calms me down in this place." dont flow well, and have weird word-choice. "-but not like this mess-" is the main contributor; it can be somewhat hard to understand. Another example being: "Every now and then, a female automated voice says calmly, “Please remain at your workstation." This overall feels strangely worded, and can also be hard to understand.

The concept is definitely unique; there aren't many levels based around NASA.}}<br>

<div style="background: #000000; border:4px solid #073763; border-radius: 8px; color:#FFFFFF; font-family:IM Fell English; padding:5px 10px;">
{{Image Banner|image=Ebene 104 Blau.png|caption=The darkness gives you a feeling of calm..}}
{{Quote|I've always wanted to work at NASA, but not like this mess.. the darkness is the only thing that calms me down in this place.|Janurary 9, 1968}}
{{Alt Class|ent=2|env=4|ext=3|noname=104|no=104}}
'''Level 104''', also known as ''"Hallo, das ist Jester 2!"'' or ''"NASA Dunkelheit"'' is the 105<sup>th</sup> level of '''[[The Backrooms]]''' and is a place that hypnotises people to stay in '''Level 104'''.
{{Underline|1069b9}}<div align="center"><font size="6"><span style="text-shadow: 0px 0px 10px #1069b9, 0px 0px 5px #1069b9, 0px 0px 10px #1069b9">< Description</span></font></div>{{Underline|1069b9}}
{{Blurimage|file=Ebene 104.png|caption=An image of some computers mixed with the darkness in '''Level 104'''.|hovertext=I got an invitation to join NASA. I went there and.. this is not what I expected. Was I late?}}{{Blurimage|file=Ebene 104 Unheimlich.webp|caption=A hallway leading to one of the danger zones in '''Level 104'''.|hovertext=DON'T LISTEN TO THE SPEAKERS.}}'''Level 104''' looks like an old NASA executive wing that has been forgotten. It has long beige hallways, low acoustic ceilings, and rows of old CRT monitors sitting on temporary folding tables. There are slight smells of dust, ozone, and old insulation in the air. Fluorescent lighting hums all the time and sometimes flickers in patterns that look like Morse code, but there is no confirmed translation.
<br>
The architecture loops in subtle ways. For example, halls connect to each other again after a few minutes of walking, and offices that look the same repeat with small changes like coffee stains, mission patches, or old launch schedules stuck to the corkboards. There are faded labels identifying most of the rooms, such as Telemetry, Payload Review, or Trajectory Analysis, but none of them have working terminals, just powered-on displays showing frozen or static models.
<br>
<br>
One of '''Level 104's''' distinguishing features is ambient sounds. From inaccessible areas of the level, explorers often report muffled countdowns, quiet keyboard tapping, or distant PA announcements. Every now and then, a female automated voice says calmly, “Please remain at your workstation." Following these signals frequently takes one farther into unstable areas, yet ignoring them seems to have no immediate repercussions.
<br>
{{Blurimage|file=Level 104...png|caption=Another image of one of the danger zones in '''Level 104'''.|hovertext=Sie beobachten mich ständig.}}
Unless disturbed, the entities encountered here are usually passive. The most prevalent are Observers, which are humanoid silhouettes that disappear when approached and are typically seen standing at the far ends of hallways. Technicians, who look like blurred office workers constantly adjusting invisible equipment, are less common. Since extended eye contact has been associated with memory loss and spatial disorientation, direct interaction with either entity type is not advised.
<br>
<br>
A number of ''conference zones'' serve as somewhat secure locations in '''Level 104'''. Although supplies are practically nonexistent, [[Object 1|Almond Water]] has been discovered inside abandoned coolers with the NASA emblem. Occasionally, Wi-Fi signals show up but are unable to establish a connection with any known network. Writing on whiteboards stays there even after it's been erased and slowly turns back into models of satellites or launch vehicles.
<br>
<br>
In '''Level 104''', time acts strangely. While wall clocks show launch times from decades ago, wristwatches can advance hours in minutes or stop completely. Some rovers claim to have seen Earth through reinforced observation windows, but they were always silent and in low orbit. Every attempt to break these windows has been unsuccessful.
<br>
<br>
There are noticeable psychological effects in '''Level 104'''. Extended exposure creates a sense of professional duty, making explorers feel obliged to “report in” or look for supervisors who don’t exist. Some people start to organize their papers in order, set up their monitors, or play simulated games. You should leave right away if this behavior doesn't stop. People all over the world have had their hopes and dreams destroyed in '''Level 104'''. It sounds like their hopes and dreams of going to space are stuck in a loop of red tape.
<br>
If you listen to '''Level 104''', it sounds like the goals and dreams of people all over the world that have been stuck in '''[[The Void|limbo]]'''. It doesn't kill right away, but over time it takes over and turns life into a habit.
